{
  "case_id": "D2N172",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "soap",
  "summary_text": "S:\nThe patient reports a stressful winter and spring, compounded by onboarding new employees and staffing shortages. He indicates that his bouts of depression have been challenging recently, and he's been doing okay with zoloft 50 milligrams daily. He occasionally experiences a need for more sleep, typically waking around 5:00 AM. He reports a slight weight gain over the past month due to hosting friends on vacation at the beach, resulting in dietary changes. He denies any feelings of wanting to hurt himself or others.\n\nO:\nPhysical exam reveals clear lungs, regular heart sounds, and a grade 2 systolic ejection murmur, which is unremarkable. Extremities are normal with no edema. Weight is slightly elevated. No other physical exam findings were noted.\n\nA:\nThe patient's primary problem is depression, with a history of high blood pressure and hypertension. His current medications, zoloft and lisinopril, are appropriate. The recent weight gain and stressful life events are contributing factors to his depression.\n\nP:\nOrder a refill on the patient's zoloft 50 milligrams daily. Continue lisinopril 5 milligrams daily. Schedule a follow-up appointment in one month to assess his progress and adjust treatment as needed. Counsel the patient on lifestyle modifications to manage stress and support his mental health.",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nHistory of depression.\n\nHISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS\n\nRoy Sanchez is a 50-year-old male who comes in with a history of depressionand high blood pressure. He presents today for abnormal labs.\n\nHe states it has been a pretty stressful winter and spring, as they have been very short-staffed at work. The patient admits to recent weight gain. He has been hosting friends over vacation and at the beach this summer so the diet is off the charts out the window.\n\nThe patient has a history of depression and is doing well. He has been consistent with utilizing his Zoloft 50 mg a day. The patient states this has been a challenging year and a half. He is sleeping okay at night, occasionally waking up at 5 a.m. Denies thoughts of self-harm or suicidal ideation\n\nHis high blood pressure has been under good control recently\n\nREVIEW OF SYSTEMS\n\n• Constitutional: Endorses weight gain.\n• Psychiatric:   Endorses stress.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAMINATION\n\n• Respiratory: Lungs are clear to auscultation bilaterally. No wheezes, rales, or rhonchi.\n• Cardiovascular: Regular rate. Grade 2 systolic ejection murmur. No gallops or rubs. No extra heart sounds.\n\nASSESSMENT AND PLAN\n\nRoy Sanchez is a 50-year-old male who comes in with a history of depression and high blood pressure. He presents today for abnormal labs.\n\nHypertension.\n• Medical Reasoning: Blood pressure is well controlled at this time.\n• Medical Treatment: He will continue lisinopril 5 mg daily.\n\nDepression.\n• Medical Reasoning: He is doing well with Zoloft 50 mg daily.\n• Medical Treatment: He will continue Zoloft 50 mg daily. This was refilled today.\n\nPatient Agreements: The patient understands and agrees with the recommended medical treatment plan.",
